Forecasting: Principles & Practice

  1. For each of the following series, make a graph of the data with forecasts using the most appropriate of the four benchmark methods: mean, naive, seasonal naive or drift. In each case, do you think the forecasts are reasonable? If not, how could they be improved?

(a) Annual bituminous coal production (19201968). Data set bicoal.

library(fpp)
plot(bicoal)

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(meanf(bicoal, h=20))
plot(rwf(bicoal, h=20))
plot(snaive(bicoal, h=20))
plot(rwf(bicoal, drift=TRUE, h=20))

Visi, iskyrus mean prognoz, atrodo priimtini.

(b) Price of chicken (19241993). Data set chicken.

plot(chicken)

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(meanf(chicken, h=10))
plot(naive(chicken, h=20))
plot(snaive(chicken, h=20))
plot(rwf(chicken, drift=TRUE, h=20))

Antroji ir treioji prognozs atrodo logikiausiai (pirmoji akivaizdiai netinka, ketvirtoji prognozuoja dar didesn kritim, nors atrodo, kad duomenys madaug nusistovjo).

(c) Monthly total of people on unemployed benefits in Australia (January 1956July 1992). Data set dole.

plot(dole)

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(meanf(dole, h=20))
plot(naive(dole, h=20))
plot(snaive(dole, h=20))
plot(rwf(dole, drift=TRUE, h=20))
